description:
The fashion and textile industry is currently undergoing a green revolution, driven by a concern for the environmental and social impact of fashion and textile materials, products, processes and systems.

 Research in this field crosses the disciplines of technology, enterprise and design, and proposals are sought that address one of the following topics:

 Performance and properties of sustainable materials including natural fibre biomaterials, natural dye colouration, and/or the development of alternatives to traditional, polluting materials;
 Fibre recycling technologies, textile waste technologies, life-cycle analysis of materials, and/or environmental management frameworks;
 Sustainable fashion and textile business models, including textile manufacturing practices, circular economy development models, and/or sustainable industry supply chains;
 Sustainable fashion retail and consumption models, including the future of retail spaces and/or the impact of technological innovations;
 The role of consumer psychology, social movements (e.g. veganism), changing social values and social policy frameworks;
 The marketing of sustainability in the context of so-called greenwashing;
 Sustainable fashion and textile design practice models, from commercial large-scale to independent micro-practices.

The use of nanoparticles has been a promising way to develop performance textiles, although durability and comfort remain issues in the potential application of the technology. Similarly, the scaling up of nanofibres continues to present a challenge to their application. This project has a number of aims, including the growing of nanoparticles on textiles and the development of novel methods of synthesis, and the theory and method of electrospinning in the fabrication of nanofibres.

 Research proposals are sought that address one of the following topics:

 The development of carbon fibre-reinforced thermoplastic composites;
 The development of spacer fabric with CNT-reinforced nanofibres for impact protection;
 Novel electrospinning systems for the scalable production of nanofibres;
 Nanomaterials/fibrous nanocomposite systems for multiple applications;
 The use of nanodiamond/selenium within fibrous systems for the development of medical textiles;
 The design, modelling and engineering of compression garments;
 Braided 3D pre-form structures for fibre-reinforced composites;
 Modelling of the protection and thermal comfort of semi-permeable PPE.

Innovations in advanced materials and performance textiles are required to confront a range of extreme environments, from the heat encountered in firefighting, to chemical, biological and other hazardous materials, to the stresses involved in space travel, to protective garments for law enforcement officers.

 Research proposals are sought that address one of the following topics:

 The development of compression garments and gloves for astronauts;
 The design and evaluation, including through the use of the school’s new flame mannikin, of functional firefighting garments;
 The development of CBRN protective textiles;
 The design of body armour for stab and ballistic protection;
 Ergonomic performance evaluation of garments;
 The improvement of UV-blocking and antibacterial properties of protective materials;
 The coating of textiles with nanomaterials for multiple applications
 The development of nanodiamond/textile composites.

Research in this field lies at the intersection of the disciplines of design and enterprise, and proposals are sought that address one of the following topics

 Practice-based and practice-led investigations of diverse forms of fashion and textile practice;
 Innovations in the communication of fashion though image, writing and performance, including its recent adoption of innovative technologies such as VR and AR and/or its increasingly diverse forms of dissemination through publication;
 Contemporary self-critical reflection upon and engagement with fashion by practitioners and writers both within and outside the academy;
 New models for the teaching and communication of fashion and textile design practice, including the foregrounding of practice-based thinking and/or the social and environmental responsibility of fashion and textile practices;
 Recent developments in the relationship between local and global systems of fashion, in its cultural, political and economic aspects;
 New forms of collaborative and cross-disciplinary relationships between practitioners in fashion and textiles and practitioners in fields such as industrial and product design, architecture and urban design, performance, photography, film and the visual arts, and/or actors and critics working in fields such as public policy or social activism.

The identification and analysis of textile composition and behaviour has important applications in a range of areas including defence and forensics and as protection against fraud and counterfeiting.

 Research proposals are sought that address one of the following topics:

 Hyperspectral analysis of fibre material and textile digital signal processing, with applications for the development and detection of camouflage and counterfeit materials;
 Bloodstain pattern analysis, with applications in the field of forensic science;
 Analysis of fabric wetting and the wicking of liquids, in the development of innovative materials for comfort and/or for forensic fibre identification;
 Artificial intelligence tools and developing technologies to provide forensic evidence and to identify the origin of textiles, including, for example, the identification of Australian wool, the origin of animal furs and skins, the DNA analysis of textile fibres, and/or the integration of fibre-based RFID technology for individual textile identification, life cycle studies, and supply chain tracking.

This project will explore the impacts of climate change on energy consumption and thermal comfort of residential buildings in Australia under a various climate change scenarios. The candidate will work with leading sustainability scientists at RMIT and CSIRO, using cutting edge numerical simulation tools and experimental data to help deliver the next generation of efficient and healthy residential building designs for Australia. The key objectives of the research project are as follows: •Using simulation tools, determine the impacts of climate change on the energy consumption and potential for summer overheating of typical residential buildings under various Australian climate conditions;
  •Identify the potential measures for reducing overheating of highly energy efficient Australian residential buildings under current and future climates; and
  •Use these findings to develop strategies to help governments and industry deliver the next generation of efficient, healthy new and retro-fitted buildings to improve performance under current and future warming climates.
